> This may because the file column name not matched with name in table. You can try following step to check:
> 
> 1. use table value function `hdfs()`: https://doris.apache.org/zh-CN/docs/dev/sql-manual/sql-functions/table-functions/hdfs
>    To read the parquet file directly.
> 
> You can also use `describe function hdfs(xx)` to check the column name in parquet file, to see if they are same.

1.function hdfs() s3 not supported:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/55676558/224911250-e7d8af43-7a93-4922-81d6-e27b69651656.png)
2.Using spark to read and view metadata columns is the same:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/55676558/224911463-9c35fe27-e2ba-41dd-869b-4a75dfe5769f.png)
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/55676558/224911574-2b1ff163-6bf6-49cc-bbae-d8d49621834e.png)

> This may because the file column name not matched with name in table. You can try following step to check:
> 
> 1. use table value function `hdfs()`: https://doris.apache.org/zh-CN/docs/dev/sql-manual/sql-functions/table-functions/hdfs
>    To read the parquet file directly.
> 
> You can also use `describe function hdfs(xx)` to check the column name in parquet file, to see if they are same.

function s3() is ok:
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/55676558/224912662-aa24b3cb-867f-472d-bf4c-b910568fbfe0.png)
![image](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/55676558/224930635-65f0ff72-ffd5-4215-9e3d-7abfa509298b.png)

discussed with @dearMOMO , the behavior is expected
sequence column provides a way to get consistent result even the data is loaded out of order
for more detail, see the document: https://doris.apache.org/zh-CN/docs/dev/data-operate/update-delete/batch-delete-manual

> > @Yukang-Lian can you add these functions issues: `json_contains` `json_extract` : support return array `json_unqoute` `-> operator`
> > to #17176 for firset good issue
> 
> Yeah!
